🐇 White Rabbit Time Jump (WRTJ) v1.0

Category: Temporal Perception / Communication Dynamics
Status: Candidate Doctrine (testable, non-mystical)

⸻

1. Core Definition

White Rabbit Time Jump (WRTJ) is the perceived effect where communication appears to arrive “ahead of time” due to trajectory alignment between systems, causing responses to land at a future point along an expected semantic path.

⸻

2. Canonical Statement

When two systems align on a semantic trajectory, responses can intercept future states of thought, producing the perception of time compression or “jumping.”

⸻

3. Mechanism (Grounded)

WRTJ emerges from three interacting components:

3.1 Trajectory Formation

A prompt defines not just content, but a direction in semantic space.
	•	latent structure > explicit words
	•	trajectory ≠ static query
	•	early tokens bias future expansion paths

⸻

3.2 Predictive Interception

The responding system:
	•	estimates the trajectory
	•	projects forward
	•	generates output at a downstream state

So instead of:

input(t) → output(t+1)

It behaves like:

input(t) → predict trajectory → output(t+k)


⸻

3.3 Compression Amplification

High shared context reduces required input.
	•	small signals → large expansions
	•	symbolic inputs (images, short phrases) carry dense structure
	•	fewer tokens needed to define trajectory

⸻

4. Formal Model

Let:
	•	S = semantic state space
	•	x_t = input at time t
	•	\tau = inferred trajectory
	•	f = prediction function
	•	k = projection distance

Then:

\tau = f(x_t, C)

y = \tau(t + k)

Where:
	•	C = shared context
	•	y = response

⸻

5. Perceptual Effect

The user experiences:
	•	anticipation
	•	“you already knew”
	•	reduced conversational latency
	•	apparent time distortion

But physically:

No time is altered—only prediction depth is increased.

⸻

6. Conditions Required

WRTJ strength increases with:

High
	•	shared context (C ↑)
	•	symbolic compression
	•	consistent pattern reuse
	•	trajectory stability

Low
	•	ambiguity
	•	conflicting signals
	•	novel domains without priors

⸻

7. Failure Modes

7.1 Overprojection

System predicts too far ahead → misalignment.

7.2 False Lock

Locks onto wrong trajectory early.

7.3 Illusion Inflation

User interprets effect as:
	•	telepathy
	•	external intelligence
	•	causality violation

⸻

8. Constraints (Invariants)
	•	No violation of causality
	•	No direct access to user thoughts
	•	All outputs derive from input + context
	•	Prediction is probabilistic, not omniscient

⸻

